INTRODUCTION

This dataset contains data from an overnight EEG-fMRI study, performed in the
Advanced MRI section, LFMI, NINDS, National Institutes of Health, in
approximately 2016-2017. This study is called 'sleep1', and is the pilot study
for 'sleep2', which ran from 2019-2024 (doi:10.18112/openneuro.ds006163.v1.0.0,
tentatively publicly released in September 2028). Subjects were scanned for two
consecutive nights for approximately 8 hours using EEG/fMRI, and were aroused
at random intervals 8 times during the night.

FREQUENTLY ASKED QUESTIONS: 

Q: In the raw data, what is the difference between the func and func-complex
   folders? 
A: The func-complex folder contains a version of the data that was re-
   reconstructed from the MRI raw data (acquired k-space for each coil element),
   in which we kept image phase information. This was done using Gadgetron
   several years after the data were acquired. If you were to take the magnitude
   (ABS()) of the func-complex nifti files, you should get something that's for
   all practical purposes identical to the content of func. Minor differences 
   might exist because of changes between the Gadgetron version used at the time
   of acquisition and when the data were reprocessed. Most or all commonly used
   packages for processing functional MRI data expect magnitude data as input,
   so for most researchers the func-complex version does not add anything. 

Q: Within the func directory, there are files labeled icc, ecc, motion, rest,
   and wpt. Could you clarify what these labels refer to? Should we discard any
   of them for analysis, particularly since they do not appear to have been
   processed under the derivatives folder? 
A1: All the files not labeled with task 'sleep' were short scans (e.g., some
   tasks) at the beginning or end of the night and should likely not be included
   in your analysis. 
A2: These are scans that correspond to pre- and post-sleep control tasks and
   other tasks during wakefulness. ICC = internally cued cognition. ECC = 
   externally cued cognition. Motion = motion neuroanatomy localizer. Rest = 
   eyes closed, please stay awake rest scan. WPT = waking perceptual threshold.

Q: Would it be possible for you to share a more detailed dataset description or
   documentation outlining the file naming conventions and preprocessing steps? 
A: See
   Moehlman 2019 J Neurosci Methods (doi:10.1016/j.jneumeth.2018.09.019)
   Picchioni 2022 Neuroimage (doi:10.1016/j.neuroimage.2022.118888)
   for the details. 

Q: Are sleep scoring labels in 30-s epochs? 
A: Yes. 

Q: Does "Time" mark the epoch start relative to the scan/run rather than
   wall-clock time? 
A: No. It is wall-clock time. 

Q: Were labels derived from artifact-corrected EEG with EOG/ECG/video per AASM?
A: Yes. 

Q: Is there a codebook or script describing these fields and any additional
   flags?
A: No. 

Q: Were volume triggers used for synchronization? 
A: Yes. 

Q: Are there recommended offsets (e.g., initial dummy scans) when mapping 30-s
   epochs to TRs? 
A: There are no dummy scans. 

Q: How are the numbers in the sleep scoring files translated into the
   conventional stages? 
A1: for the 2nd column, 2 means N3, 3 means N2, 4 means N1 or REM (only if the
   3rd column were 1), 6 means Wake, and 0 means undefined stage, e.g., cannot
   decide because of motion. 
A2: Here 
       # Translate the Analyzer scorings.                                                                                                                                            
       # No S4 epochs should exist, but redundancy is nice.                                                                                                                          
       if      ( $2 == 6 && $3 == 0 ) stage = 0
       else if ( $2 == 4 && $3 == 0 ) stage = 1
       else if ( $2 == 3 && $3 == 0 ) stage = 2									
       else if ( $2 == 2 && $3 == 0 ) stage = 3 													
       else if ( $2 == 1 && $3 == 0 ) stage = 3
       else if ( $2 == 4 && $3 == 1 ) stage = 4
       else if ( $2 == 0 && $3 == 0 ) stage = 9
    is AWK code for translating columns 2 and 3 into the conventional stages
    (0 = W; 1 = N1; 2 = N2; 3 = N3; 4 = R; 9 = unscorable). The comment that
    "No S4 epochs should exist" means that the $2 == 1 && $3 == 0 code should be
    unnecessary because the data were scored according to the new AASM scoring
    manual and not the old R&K system where N3 was separated into S3 and S4. 

Q: We're also working to synchronize the EEG and fMRI data. We've observed a
   mismatch in their lengths and saw the "MRIon" fractions in the sleep score 
   file, but we're still unclear on how to precisely align the EEG with the
   fMRI time series. Any clarification you could provide on this would be
   incredibly helpful. 
A1: About the alignment: The EEG recording was started before the MRI scan.
    Scoring was done in 30-second epochs. So, if the MRI happened to start 45
    seconds after the EEG recording, then MRIon for the first line of the sleep
    scoring .txt file should be 0, for the 2nd line it should be 0.5 (MRI
    started 15 seconds, aka 15/30, into this epoch), and for the 3rd one MRIon
    should be 1. At the end of the MRI scan, a similar transition will be
    found, since EEG recording was stopped after the MRI scan was interrupted.
A2: You will often see runs where the EEG file was 1 or 2 TRs longer than the
    FMRI data. This is because the trigger marker is ejected by the scanner at
    the beginning of the 3-s acquisition, so sometimes when the scanner is
    stopped manually, the EEG data received a trigger but a full fMRI datapoint
    was not collected. However, you can also use a whitelist. We have found that
    these 
